Microservices design patterns are solutions to common challenges in distributed systems.
They help manage communication, failures, data consistency, and deployment.
Key categories include architectural patterns (API Gateway, Service Discovery), resilience patterns (Circuit Breaker, Retry), and data patterns (Saga, CQRS).
They ensure scalability, fault tolerance, and loose coupling between services.
Event-driven communication using Kafka is commonly used in microservices.
These patterns are widely implemented using Spring Boot and Spring Cloud.
They are essential for building reliable enterprise applications.

1. Architectural Patterns
   Architectural patterns define the overall structure of a microservices system.
   They decide how services are organized and how clients interact with them.
   These patterns help achieve scalability, flexibility, and loose coupling.
   They also simplify communication and service management.
   Common examples include API Gateway, Service Discovery, and Database per Service.
 ->  API Gateway – Single entry point for all client requests
 ->  Service Registry & Discovery – Services find each other dynamically (like Eureka)
 ->  Database per Service – Each service has its own DB

2. Resilience Patterns
   Resilience patterns are used to handle failures in microservices systems.
   They ensure the system remains available and stable even when some services fail.
   These patterns prevent cascading failures across services.
   They improve fault tolerance and reliability of applications.
   Common examples include Circuit Breaker, Retry, Timeout, and Bulkhead.
  -> Circuit Breaker – Stops calls to failing service
  -> Retry Pattern – Retry failed requests
  -> Timeout Pattern – Stop waiting after certain time
 ->  Bulkhead – Isolate failures (like ship compartments)

3. Data Management Patterns
   Data Management Patterns handle data consistency across multiple microservices.
   Since each service has its own database, transactions become distributed.
   These patterns ensure data integrity without using a single centralized transaction.
   They help manage eventual consistency and data synchronization.
   Common patterns include Saga, CQRS, and Event Sourcing.
  -> Saga Pattern – Manage distributed transactions
  -> CQRS – Separate read and write operations
  -> Event Sourcing – Store events instead of state

4. Communication Patterns
   Communication patterns define how microservices interact with each other.
   They can be synchronous (real-time) or asynchronous (event-based).
   These patterns help achieve loose coupling and scalability.
   They also impact performance and reliability of the system.
   Common approaches include REST APIs and message queues like Kafka or RabbitMQ.
  -> Synchronous (REST) – Direct API calls
  -> Asynchronous (Kafka/RabbitMQ) – Event-based communication

5. Deployment Patterns
   Deployment patterns define how microservices are released and updated in production.
   They help achieve zero downtime and smooth user experience.
   These patterns reduce the risk of failures during deployment.
   They allow easy rollback if something goes wrong.
   Common patterns include Blue-Green Deployment and Canary Deployment.
   They are widely used in CI/CD pipelines for safe releases.
  -> Blue-Green Deployment
  -> Canary Deployment

  🔥 What is Canary Deployment?

  Canary Deployment is a release strategy where a new version of an application is deployed to a small subset of users first,
  while the rest continue using the old version.
  It helps detect issues early before affecting all users.

  🔥 Step-by-Step Flow (Very Important)
  Deploy new version (v2) alongside old version (v1)
  Route small % of traffic to v2 (e.g., 10%)
  Monitor logs, errors, performance (using tools like Grafana, Splunk)
  If stable → gradually increase traffic (30% → 50% → 100%)
  If failure → rollback to v1 immediately